i R_1^2)^2}$.\n- Step 4: The internal pressure of the gas changes, such that it is $P_i'(\\frac{4}{3}\\pi R_1^3) = P_i(\\frac{4}{3}\\pi R_0^3)$, where $P_i = P_a$.\n- Step 5: So $P_i' = P_a(\\frac{R_0}{R_1})^3$.\n- Step 6: Balancing pressures on the bubble: $P_{a} = P_i' +  \\frac{1}{2 \\varepsilon_{0}} \\frac{q^2}{(4 \\pi R_1^2)^2}$, so $P_{a} = P_{a} \\left(\\frac{R_{0}}{R_{1}}\\right)^{3} + \\frac{q^{2}}{32 \\pi^{2} \\varepsilon_{0} R_{1}^{4}}$.\n- Step 7: Dividing by $P_a$ and rearranging gives: $1 = \\left(\\frac{R_{0}}{R_{1}}\\right)^{3} + \\frac{q^{2}}{32 \\pi^{2} \\varepsilon_{0} R_{1}^{4} P_a}$, which can be written as $\\left(\\frac{R_{1}}{R_{0}}\\right)^{4} - \\left(\\frac{R_{1}}{R_{0}}\\right) - \\frac{q^{2}}{32 \\pi^{2} \\varepsilon_{0} R_{0}^{4} P_{a}} = 0$.\n\nEXPLANATION:\nTo solve this, The electric field on the surface of the bubble due to its own charge is $E_{q} = \\frac{q}{4 \\pi \\varepsilon_{0} R_{1}^{2}}$. After computing, the result is 0 1.\n\nANSWER: 0 1"}]}
