 the first collision of the wooden board with the barrier, the direction of the board's acceleration is downward along the incline.\n- Step 2: Let the magnitude of the acceleration be $a_{1}$.\n- Step 3: According to Newton's second law, we have:\n- Step 4: [ m g\\sin\\theta + \\mu m g\\cos\\theta = m a_{1} ]\n- Step 5: Solving this, we obtain:\n- Step 6: [ a_{1} = 11\\,\\mathrm{m}/\\mathrm{s}^{2} ]\n- Step 7: After the wooden board collides with the barrier for the first time, the direction of the block's acceleration is upward along the inclined plane.\n- Step 8: Let the magnitude of the acceleration be $a_{2}$.\n- Step 9: According to Newton's second law, we have:\n- Step 10: [\n- Step 11: \\mu m g\\cos\\theta - m g\\sin\\theta = m a_{2}\n- Step 12: ]\n- Step 13: Solving this, we obtain:\n- Step 14: [\n- Step 15: a_{2} = 1\\,\\mathrm{m}/\\mathrm{s}^{2}\n- Step 16: ]\n- Step 17: After the wooden plank moving upward along the inclined plane collides with the barrier for the first time, it takes time $t$ for the plank and the block to reach a common velocity $v$.\n- Step 18: For the plank and the block, according to the laws of uniformly accelerated linear motion, we have respectively: $v=-v_{0}+a_{1}t$, $v=v_{0}-a_{2}t$, solving which gives $v=2.5\\mathrm{m/s}$.\n- Step 19: Taking the downward direction along the incline as positive, let the displacement of the plank moving upward along the incline after the first collision with the barrier be $x_{1}$.\n- Step 20: According to the laws of uniformly accelerated linear motion, we have: $v_{0}^{2}-v^{2}=2a_{1}x_{1}$, solving for $x_{1}=0.125\\mathrm{m}$.\n\nEXPLANATION:\nTo solve this, After the first collision of the wooden board with the barrier, the direction of the board's acceleration is downward along the incline. After computing, the result is 0.125 m.\n\nANSWER: 0.125 m"}]}
